<center>"If you're frightened of dying and then you hold on you'll see devils tearing your life away. But, if you've made your peace then the devils are really angels Freeing you from the Earth"</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uaalek.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aalek</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Blessed Protector</span><br>  Posts: 442<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/25/02 12:37:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15901.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: OT: How easy is it to build your own computer?</span><hr size=1> I'd say it *can* be easy, but it can also be downright frustrating.  There is nothing difficult about the actual steps you take to assemble a computer from the various parts.  The biggest hurdle is probably learning all of the terminology so that you buy parts that are compatible with each other (like the right type of CPU for the motherboard, the right kind of RAM, a case that will fit the motherboard, etc.).<br>
<br>
You also need to be a bit careful with a couple of the steps, like putting the heatsink on the CPU without breaking the CPU, and putting just about everything into the motherboard without frying something with static electricity.  Nothing that hard to do but just things to watch out for.<br>
<br>
The harder and often frustrating part is getting the operating system and device drivers to work.  I've built several computers and that's always been my biggest headache.  The hardware might work fine, but if the Microsoft OS doesn't recognize it right away, it might not start up or the OS installation might fail.  Once the OS does get installed and you can boot it, some of the devices might not work until you get the right drivers installed.<br>
<br>
I've had bad and good experiences with that--I've had W2K not want to install at all, and had to do a lot of hit-and-miss troubleshooting to get through it.  I've also had a pretty smooth sailing effort where I really didn't have any significant problems.<br>
<br>
It's also not that hard to get some defective parts.  I've had defective RAM and video cards before.  The frustrating part is that with some of those core components it may not be easy to tell what is causing the problem.<br>
<br>
I would suggest that if you go into this, go in with the expectation that you will have some of these problems, things won't work right after you're done plugging everything in, and you might need to spend a fair amount of time getting them to work.<br>
<br>
There are also some &quot;middle ground&quot; solutions.  For one of my computers I bought a &quot;bare bones kit&quot;, which included the motherboard, a CPU and heatsink, the RAM.  It wasn't much more expensive than if I bought the parts separately, in fact it might have been cheaper.  It came assembled and tested so I didn't have to mess with that part of it.<br>
<br>
It would also help you a lot if you had a &quot;techie&quot; friend you could call if you have questions or need to be talked through something.  No one is going to give you full technical support for what you're doing, they will only support whatever part(s) you bought from them.  The various manuals that come with the parts will probaby include most of the information you need, but it might be difficult to decipher the first time.<br>
<br>
When I'm on the market for a desktop computer, I usually do look at the brand-name models for comparison, because it would save me the time of putting it together and troubleshooting any problems.  I rarely find a configuration that exactly matches what I want though, and if I do then it is usually a few hundred dollars more than what I would pay building it myself, so I always end up building it myself.<br>
<br>
I guess the bottom line of what I'm saying is that it can be very hit or miss.  Depending on what parts you buy and whether or not any of them are defective, you could have a relatively easy or hard time with it.  You'd definitely have some learning to do but it's not insurmountable, like I said it's mostly just learning terminology. <p><BR>
