<br>
For the most part pluggin/screwing things together is easy. Read your motherboard manual and its usually pretty epclicit on settings. As far as plugging thigns in, usually they can only go in 1 spot, and the motyherboard manual will be explicit on that as well.<br>
<br>
Basically you need to read any warnings/jumper settings first and you shouldnt have many problems. ALWAYS make sure to ground yourself before you touch anything in a computer. A small static charge on yoru skin is plenty to fry a microchip. With that said i have never fryed anything, and ive messed with the guts of computers a lot. All ya gotta do is frequently touch a grounded object and you will be fine. An easy way to do this is to plug in your case when you are putting it together, and just frequently touch the case. WARNING tho, on atx motherboards they are active even when the case is off. You will almost certainly be using an atx board so make sure that you dont plug in the board till last if you are gonna use this method of ensuring a ground.<br>
<br>
Read your motherboard manual on bios settings before you let the system fully boot and make any necessary changes. Anything in the bios that you dont know what it means, dont mess with it.<br>
<br>
After you got it bootable, install your os and get it networkable first. Download the lastest drivers for all your hardware and install them 1 by 1 rebooting each time.<br>
<br>
Baring any funky issues thats it.<br>
<br>
As far as what hardware to use, do some research beforehand. www.tomshardware.com is a good source. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uketherami.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kether Am I</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Holy Defender</span><br>  Posts: 584<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/25/02 2:23:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15901.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: OT: How easy is it to build your own computer?</span><hr size=1> There ARE a few pieces of advice I would offer:<br>
<br>
1. Make SURE you are building the computer near a place where you have web access.  No doubt there will be driver updates, installation instructions, bios upgrades, or general technical advise on the web that will aid you.  It is *much* harder to get these things when your only PC is still in pieces ;-).<br>
<br>
2. MOST PC components are easy to install.  These include MB, Ram, power supply, hard drives, cd drives, and floppy drives.  Some can be complicated with either the physical or driver installation, these include video and sound.  MODEMS can be *very* difficult at times to get properly situated.<br>
<br>
3. Get and KEEP ALL support materials and documentation.<br>
<br>
4. DON'T expect fanstastic saving anymore when building your own PC.  The quantity discounts that large PC makers (like Dell) get and the commodity like nature of the final products makes it tough to take much off of their prices.  The exception would be if you have 'free' parts like existing CDRW, DVD drives, Sound/Video cards, or an OS that you are carrying over to your new self-built PC.<br>
<br>
5. DON'T build your own PC just because maker A doesn't build a system with sound X and video Y.  The lack of support for your system more than outweighs a couple FPS or esoteric feature_01.  If this point applies to you it may be worth the cost of simply bying the system and changing one component, giving the now replaced one to a friend.<br>
<br>
6. DON'T make a PC full of every new piece of hardware on the market.  The likely dozens of patches/updates and lingering incompatibilities are a headache waiting to happen.<br>
<br>
7. DON'T do 6 above unless you really don't care about cost either.  In 2-3 years you are going to replace the system anyway.  And by that time the very marginal benefits of the 'best' versus 'very good' would have meant very little, but cost a great deal.<br>
<br>
8. If you do it HAVE FUN but don't put yourself on a 24 hour deadline to have it built.  May take a few days depending on the components, your experience, and available work hours.<br>
<br>
<br>
Hope this has helped.<br>
<br>
<br>
