<br>
Building your own computer is the only way to go if computers and computer gaming is your hobby.  You save a TON of money.  I can build a system that is 2X better than a Dell or Gateway for half the cost.<br>
<br>
Here are some things that I've learned.<br>
<br>
A good video card is crucial to good 3D performance.  Right now I would suggest a card based on the NVidea Geforce 4 4200 with 128 mb of ram.  It seems to be the price/performance leader right now.  Too many Gateways and Dells are sold with obsolete or seriously gimped video cards in systems that sound pretty because they advertise the processor speed, but fall short of being a good gaming computer because a good gaming computer will have a good video card.<br>
<br>
Don't get the latest processor, it carries a price premium because it's new.  Take the price of the chip and divide it by the number of mhz the chip runs at (or the PR Rating).  This works when comparing the same brand of chip mind you.  The AMD XP 1800PR processor chip seems to be the best price right now at $85.  So 85/1800 = 4.72 cents a mhz.  The top of the line AMD XP 2200PR is $220 or 10 cents a mhz.  That's double the price...and that's the price premium.  I'd buy the 1800 chip.  Also, don't buy Intel.  They have been shafting people for a long time and their product is also much more expensive for the same processing power that AMD will give you.  Just because Intel has a faster mhz rating does not mean it's better.<br>
<br>
New processors run hot so a good processor fan is important too.  You don't  have to spend a bunch of money and get a real jazzy processor fan.  My Cooler Master fans were cheap and do the job.  Case cooling is also important.  Cases really need fans now adays.  Enermax, Antec/Cheiftech cases are good ones to get.  I like the big cases personally, but if small is the way to go, get the round IDE cables instead of the ribbon ones.  (ribbon ones usually come with your motheboard, so round IDE cables would have to be ordered extra)  Ribbon ones can block air flow and thus impede case cooling.<br>
<br>
Don't get too hung up on RAM speed.  DDR2100 is fast and is a much better value than the newer faster DDR RAM.  EQ really does run better with more memory.  Go for 512mb in a single stick.  Mushkin tricked me into buying some 'high density' RAM the other day.  I was pleasantly suprised that it works just fine, but there is a difference... although I'm not exactly sure what it is.<br>
<br>
As someone esle said... stay away from the latest to hit the market stuff.  First there is the steep price premium and second they usually don't work right untill the companies get bug report feedback and correct driver issues.<br>
<br>
Someone mentioned support.  It is true if you know nothing about computers and you venture down this road without at least a computer geek friend to help you, you could end up shelling out bucks to a local computer shop fixing your stuff and miss out on the cost savings and some of the education of it.  Personally I have my brother to call up and say &quot;my X is doing Y and I've worked for 5 hours trying to figure it out and it still won't work&quot; and occasionally have something obvious pointed out to me.  I can't tell you how many times I've bought a new motherboard and processor and video card and hook them all up reall nice and pretty like and press the power button and get no response.  .  <br>
<br>
Read sites such as www.tomshardware.com and www.anandtech.com  Anandtech even has a book that talks about and tells you how a novice can build their own computer and what is what.  I haven't bought it, so I can't say how good it is, but if it's as good as his site, then it should be a good book.  <br>
<br>
To buy, I use www.pricewatch.com   I end up finding that www.newegg.com usually has the cheapest prices.<br>
<br>
I don't buy barebones kits because they are usually the older items the vendor is trying to get rid of.<br>
<br>
Don't neglect other things that make sitting at your computer a joy.  I use a banquet table from an Office Depot as my desk.  Lots of legroom since I'm a big guy, my legs actually fit underneath it.  A comfortable chair is important.  Logitech mice have always fit my hand well and the optical mice are excellent.  Need the wheel thing too for easy message scrolling in game.  19&quot; moniter is a minimum.<br>
<br>
I suggest putting money aside each month for your next computer upgrade.  To keep with the times, expect to spend $200-600 a year for upgrades.  Put off buying new stuff untill 1) the price has dropped as low as it will go 2) you can't take it anymore.  If you plan to do a whole system upgrade, then save up and buy it all at one time.<br>
<br>
